<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-598-056  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 598 056.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 4 1989 v23 n36 p21(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Telecommuting is here to stay.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gordon, Gil.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Telecommuting is still growing as a trend, but not as quickly asanalysts had projected during the mid-1980's.andP;  Such problems ashow to beat gridlock commuter traffic, how to boost employeeproductivity and keep them happy, how to cut operating expenses,are still part of the motivating forces behind telecommuting.andO;Technological barriers that once existed are now being eliminated.andO;Microcomputer prices have fallen, telecommunications serviceofferings are expanding, and networking is ubiquitous and betterunderstood.andP;  A close-supervision management style is anathema totelecommuting, and in well-run programs, for a few days a week,most employees manage their time at home well.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TelecommutingTrendsErgonomicsManagement StyleProductivity.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>